@nlewo IMO, what really matters is whether `docker load` supports it, which it does. This code was written before `1.12.0` was released, and it works with older Docker releases. If you do a `docker save` of an import of our output, you get the "new" format which indicates that Docker clearly knows what's going on. Can you give an example of an image which was not correctly handled by `skopeo` or Docker because of these issues?

I also am not a huge fan of decompressing blobs through `skopeo`, these sorts of tricks (trying to work around the `Put...` interfaces by lying about the checksum of a blob) always results in a bunch of issues. Not to mention I believe it would break signing, no?

Another point is that we **are** following the `v1.2` Docker "spec". It clearly allows you to specify any paths for the `Config` and `Layers`. We just aren't producing the same paths as Docker, which isn't a problem and I don't see why it would be (the spec allows it explicitly). You could argue compression isn't explicitly allowed, but since there's only two implementations of this format (`skopeo` and Docker) I would be fairly confident in saying that this counts as consensus on a spec extension.

@mtrmac I mean this ["spec"](https://github.com/moby/moby/blob/749d90e10f989802638ae542daf54257f3bf71f2/image/spec/v1.2.md#combined-image-json--filesystem-changeset-format). I used the term "legacy" because this is what the Docker code uses to talk about these images (https://github.com/moby/moby/blob/master/image/tarexport/tarexport.go#L12).

@cyphar as said by @mtrmac, we plan to use Skopeo to get images from the registry to the format that is used by `docker save`. These images can then be used by tools that build images without relying on Docker (mainly because it's hard to use Docker in reprocible environments).

@cyphar With `docker  1.12.6`, I get the image ` ubuntu@sha256:45b23dee08af5e43a7fea6c4cf9c25ccf269ee113168c19722f87876677c5cb2` with skopeo to the `docker-archive` format. I then loaded this `tgz` and saved it with docker. The resulting `tgz` format is the [v1.2](https://github.com/moby/moby/blob/749d90e10f989802638ae542daf54257f3bf71f2/image/spec/v1.2.md#combined-image-json--filesystem-changeset-format) one. But maybe, my docker version is too old.

One last thing is that the Skopeo readme says "docker-archive:path[:docker-reference] An image is stored in the docker save formated file [...]" which is not the case form my point of view.

@nlewo From that spec:

> Generally, implementations that support this version of the spec will use the `manifest.json` file if available, and older implementations will use the legacy `*/json` files and `repositories`.

Read that in context with what I’ve been telling you. There are **two** formats.
